04973nam a22007335i 9781782042389DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820423897 a10.1515/97817820423892doi  a(DE-B1597)674985  a(OCoLC)1097154454  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPR9396.9.F3bZ76 2014 7aLIT0040102bisacsh04a893.543223  aHP 4141qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/51884:116371 aMoolla, F. Fiona, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReading Nuruddin Farah :bThe individual, the novel & the idea of home /cF. Fiona Moolla.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2014] 1bJames Currey, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Defining the Individual. Conceptual & Historical Limits -- t2 From a Crooked Rib & the Bildungsroman. DEVELOPING THE SELF, DEVELOPING THE NATION -- t3 The ‘Gynocentric’ Bildungsroman . SARDINES & GIFTS -- t4 Modernism in A Naked Needle . & Sweet & Sour Milk -- t5 Close Sesame & the Representation of Heteronomy -- t6 Dissolving the Boundaries of Self & Nation . in Maps & Secrets -- t7 Reconstructing the Subject in the Third Trilogy. Links, knots & crossbones -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA close analysis of Farah's novels is used to track the contradictions implicit in the notion of the modern, disengaged self and how transformations of the novel in literary history attempt to negotiate this founding contradiction.The Somali novelist, Nuruddin Farah, is one of the most important African writers today. The central question that this book investigates is the relationship between modern identity and the novel as a genre. Nuruddin Farah's novels are shown by Moolla to encompass the history of the novel: from the 'proto-realism' of the acclaimed From a Crooked Rib to the modernism of A Naked Needle and the postmodernism of, most notably, Maps, returning almost full circle with his most recent novel Crossbones. Moolla examines his writing within the framework of Somali society and culture, Islamic traditions and political contexts, all of which are central themesin his work. She also addresses Farah's engagement with women's lives - his female characters and identities being at the heart of, rather than peripheral, to his stories - something that has distinguished him from many other male African writers. The book finally suggests that through his literary negotiation of the central contradiction of modern identity, Farah comes close to constituting a subject who no longer is transcendentally 'homeless', butfinds a home 'everywhere' - a fitting project for a writer who has been in exile for the greater part of his life. F. Fiona Moolla is a Senior Lecturer in the Faculty of Arts at the University of the Western Cape in South Africa as well as a freelance writer and published author of short stories. South Africa and Zimbabwe (pb only): Blue Weaver  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitics and literaturezSomalia. 0aPostmodernism (Literature)zSomalia. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / African.2bisacsh  aAfrican Writers.  aAfrican writers.  aF. Fiona Moolla.  aFemale Characters.  aIslamic Traditions.  aIslamic traditions.  aModern Identity.  aNuruddin Farah.  aReading Nuruddin Farah: The individual, the novel & the idea of home.  aSomali Novelist.  aSomali society.  aexile.  afemale characters.  amodern identity.  apolitical contexts.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.